%N A365079 a(n) is the number of distinct triangles with height n that can be formed with two right triangles with integer sides, either by joining them or by cutting off the smaller one from the larger one.
%C A365079 In both cases, the two right triangles must have a leg of length n. To form a triangle with height n, there are binomial(A046079(n) + 1, 2) ways to join them and binomial(A046079(n), 2) ways to cut off the smaller one from the larger one. That's a total of (A046079(n)+1, 2) + (A046079(n), 2) = A046079(n)*(A046079(n) + 1)/2 + (A046079(n) - 1)*A046079(n)/2 = (A046079(n))^2 distinct triangles with height h.
%H A365079 F. Richman, <a href="http://math.fau.edu/Richman/mla/pythag3s.htm">Pythagorean triples with leg n</a>
%H A365079 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle">Triangle</a>
%F A365079 a(n) = A046079(n)^2.
%e A365079 For height n = 9 the number of distinct triangles a(9) is 4, since there are exactly two right triangles (sides of length: 9, 12, 15) and (9, 40, 41) with leg 9 and integer sides. By joining (9, 12, 15) and (9, 12, 15), we get (15, 24, 15), by joining (9, 40, 41) and (9, 40, 41), we get (41, 80, 41), by joining (9, 12, 15) and (9, 40, 41), we get (15, 52, 41), by cutting off (9, 12, 15) from (9, 40, 41), we get (15, 28, 41).
%p A365079 A365079 := proc(n) sum(1 - ceil(i*(2*n - i)/(2*n - 2*i)) + floor(i*(2*n - i)/(2*n - 2*i)), i = 1 .. n - 1)^2; end proc; seq(A365079(n), n = 1 .. 76);
